Is there any game that epitomizes the "All that could have been" better?
>games is sells itself as open world, but the areas to explore are small corridors and large asset diahorrea areas that are very disconnected from each other. This in turn makes them feel too small and too short
>no point in open being open world when there are no activites to engage in said world
>enormous waste of resources for a multiplayer no one was ever going to go through, with each faction having their very own structure, main characters and companions, could have been spent on making alternative storylines instead
>huge waste in resources making the game a fucking rts, which could have been used to develop dungeons in which instead of using items like Zelda could have used the members' special abilities
>driving is shit, the car flips over any molehill and the terrain is cluttered with props that stop you 
>due to no area transition you have to drive all over from the last checkpoint to the place you died in. This makes it even more annoying post-game where the only checkpoints you can activate are by entering the upgrade stores that have already been rendered useless by getting all the upgrades and having a loading time of 30 seconds just to establish a spawnpoint
>Map promises way much space of what there really is, at least 1/3rd of the two last "islands" is just a bunch of mountains you can't go around
And even then, it's still one of the few games that has this metal ambience so well developed, the place is interesting to explore, and the music is killer. It enrages me how better could this game have ended up being, but even Bobby Kotick knew that Shitface was going to fuck everything up.
